Yo uso un 0,6% desde hace dos meses basado en datos en China, pero Nature acaba de compilar lo que se sabe hasta ahora. Como ven estoy usando el valor m√°s bajo y por ende estoy siendo optimista cuando hago proyecciones de casos reales. 12/ https://t.co/06nfI7aCCk
Al final IFR no ser√° muy distinto de un pa√≠s a otro, s√≥lo cambiar√° levemente por factores geogr√°ficos, econ√≥micos y sanitarios. /11

La tasa de letalidad final de la infecci√≥n (IFR en ingl√©s) ser√° mucho menor que la CFR pues dividiremos por todos los que se enfermaron, que tendremos que estimar pues es un n√∫mero que nunca se sabr√°.  10/

Realmente no, Chile tiene menos fallecidos y menos casos confirmados. Por otro lado Chile es un pa√≠s mucho m√°s peque√±o, as√≠ que la situaci√≥n es mucho m√°s preocupante, pero ese es otro tema. El siguiente gr√°fico muestra el CFR correcto (azul) y el calculado por MinSal (rojo). 9/ https://t.co/mBSurmqFRZ

Hagamos un ejemplo: Rusia tiene un poco menos de 7.700 fallecidos y un poco m√°s de 560 casos confirmados. Es decir calculando el CFR mal nos da 1,4%. Y Chile tiene ahora un CFR de 1,7% (antes de los 553 extra estaba cerca del 1%). ¬øEst√° Chile peor que Rusia? 8/

Espero ahora que quede claro que la CFR tiene comportamientos y valores muy distintos en otros pa√≠ses, as√≠ que no podemos usar CFR para compararnos con ellos, es como comparar manzanas con sand√≠as. De hecho no deber√≠amos usar CFR, no significa nada importante. 7/

As√≠ que el segundo problema es que la tasa de letalidad de casos es una medida muy variable que s√≥lo refleja los fallecidos informados y la positividad de los test, lo que a su vez depende del estado de la pandemia (comienzo, meseta, final). 6/

Dos semanas despu√©s que N aumenta, aumenta F, pues parte de los nuevos contagios fallece, y ahora el CFR vuelve a subir. En este caso si le podemos echar la culpa al virus, pero en realidad tampoco ha cambiado. 5/

Analicemos ahora que pasa en la pr√°ctica cuando calculamos CFR = F/N. Si los fallecidos F aumentan de repente como hace 2 domingos, CFR sube. Si hacemos m√°s test y la positividad aumenta, como est√° pasando ahora, N aumenta y CFR baja. En ambos casos el virus no ha cambiado. 4/

Can we answer now if the AI surgeon should be illegal? Probably should be legal, but it is not a simple question. Involves ethics, law, empathy, and other human traits.

Now you are in a dilemma as you know that the AI surgeon has a 10% advantage. But because of the unknown diversity bias, the uncertainty of a negative AI error and the faith on a positive noise, the human doctor might be equally good.

However, by Murphy‚Äôs law, you are in the middle right region of the graph, where the bottom red and the top yellow lines already crossed. Bad luck, the research papers also do not have the error distribution, so you do not really know the red lines.

Now your only choice is to do an informed guess based in how ‚Äúdifferent‚Äù you are. If you are quite different, keep the human doctor. If you are quite average (e.g., white man in the USA), you may assume that the training data has plenty of those people and you go with the AI doc.

However the research that lead to the AI surgeon is not that detailed and when you ask the manufacturer, you are told that the data is private (of course because of legal regulations that the maker has to comply with, not because they do not want anyone to audit them)
You can learn about this claim in Hinton's interview in Wired (https://t.co/egFsPzqQ0T) refuted by 8 experts in Forbes (https://t.co/7vUlPseSOy).

However, in practice you do not know that much. First, you will need to talk to the human doctor to know how complex is your case as the AI surgeon cannot explain anything. But @geoffreyhinton would say that the doctor will make up a story, not an explanation.
Hence, the accuracy depending on these factors for both doctors will look like the following graph. https://t.co/tER2cgFMU0

(2) we know the error distribution with respect to the complexity of the case (although most AI systems do not even report the average error nor they have a notion of instance complexity, but perhaps is like the graph below); and https://t.co/8R2gLL4fe8
Let‚Äôs us assume that: (1) the medical robot used good training data and has passed all legal test regulations (e.g., FDA regulations for medical devices);

Most comments to the tweet in https://t.co/ide3sk8rL8 are negative. 

But if we have only those two choices. Which one is best?

This provocative question includes a misleading dichotomy as a rational person would not decide based on just an average that you do not even know how was computed. Misleading because there is a third choice that is a much better: I want a human surgeon augmented with AI support.

One month ago, @geoffreyhinton tweeted: "... you have to choose between a black box AI surgeon that cannot explain how it works but has a 90% cure rate and a human surgeon with an 80% cure rate. Do you want the AI surgeon to be illegal?". Below my answer and my rationale follows https://t.co/znqxyUzJbY
